comments.commentBody:
@Robert Meeker
I’m with you.  If the burger is too big, then I can’t get a taste of everything else in the sandwich.  I like a good balance of meat to crunchy lettuce and onions with a thinly sliced tomato, sweet ketchup and/or barbecue sauce. I want a mix of all of that in every bite. 
If the burger or the bun are too big, that’s impossible.

Delicious. Made on a whim, so a few changes as suggested by other commenters. 
- tossed the carrots along with the cucumber and salt; 
- didn't have mentaiko or any type of fish roe on hand, subbed with 2 oz of lox and a couple splashed of fish sauce; 
- used regular mayo. 

Next time will definitely make with Kewpie mayo, it'll give the salad a more distinct flavor.

@SteveR
Best. Ever!
Haven’t been to SF in way too long, but every time I’ve gone I MUST go to TL for roast crab and these amazing noodles!

Made exactly as written it was tasty but mild and not memorable to me (maybe better quality pasta would help). So I tried a few modifications: 
1) melt anchovy or two with the butter to keep with the italian theme; 
2) extra teaspoon of oyster and fish sauce; 
3) Parmesean alone was too weak to stand up to that garlic. I used 1/4 cup parmesean plus about 1/6 cup Parmigiano Reggiano.

@Mary Fields,  your additions sound delicious. 
I had no idea potato chips in a sandwich is a thing. As a child,  I was heartily  discouraged from playing with my food and potato chips in a sandwich sounds like something a four-year-old would create in the dark.
I’ll try it though!

We made it and have two observations: 
1) Most nonstick and are not supposed to be used above medium heat, so the advised medium-high might damage the pan;
2) We used tapioca and there was a slightly weird texture to the scrambled eggs, a bit floury and mealy.
